Preheat your #oven{} to 210 degrees. Cut the @butternut squash{600%g} in half lengthways (no need to peel!) and scoop out the seeds with a #spoon{}. Slice each half into wedges as thick as your thumb. Pop your wedges into a #bowl{} and drizzle in a glug of @oil{1%glug}, a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and the @smoked paprika{1.5%tsp}. Mix well, rubbing all the flavours into the flesh of your butternut. Pop your wedges on a #baking tray{} and roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{30-35%minutes}.

Whilst your butternut roasts, get on with the rest of your prep. Remove any tough bottom from the root end of the @kalettes{1}(stems trimmed) (just like you would with brussels sprouts!) and then rinse under cold water. Keep to one side.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Remove the seeds from the @red chilli{1/4}(seeds removed and finely chopped) and chop into very small pieces. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}(roughly chopped) and then crush the @walnuts{25%g} by popping them in a #freezer bag{} and gently hitting them with the bottom of a #saucepan{}. Cut the @halloumi{1%block} into slices (allow four per person). Keep to one side.

Mix your walnuts with the @honey{3%tbsp}, a pinch of chilli and your parsley. We will drizzle this over your halloumi when it is cooked.

Heat a #frying pan{} over medium heat and add a splash of @oil{1%splash}. When the oil is hot add your kalettes and stir-fry for ~{1%minute}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} and then add your garlic and as much chilli as you fancy.

Add a splash of @water{1%splash} and cover the pan with a #lid{} or #tinfoil{}. Steam your kalettes for ~{3-4%minutes}, then remove from the pan. If your wedges are ready, turn your oven off and pop your kalettes in your oven with your wedges to keep warm.

Wipe your frying pan clean with #kitchen paper{} and pop it back on high heat. Add a splash of @oil{1%splash} and then add your halloumi slices. Cook for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

> The halloumi slices need to be golden brown so don't overcrowd the pan, cook in batches if necessary.

When all your halloumi is cooked, remove your pan from the heat and get ready to serve!

Arrange your butternut wedges on your #plate{} and fill the gaps with your kalettes. Top with your halloumi slices and drizzle over your honey and walnuts. Yum!